        <hl1>Yes, I Remember It Well</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Blaine letter on June 6 article cites implications of finding that many basic childhood recollections are highly unreliable</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In a new study of memory, researchers at Northwestern University contend that many basic childhood recollections are highly unreliable (''The Memories of Youth, Fading Fast,'' June 6).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In a new study of memory, researchers at Northwestern University contend that many basic childhood recollections are highly unreliable (''The Memories of Youth, Fading Fast,'' June 6).</p>
        <p>For instance, while 82 percent of the boys said they had been ''disciplined physically,'' as grown men only 33 percent recalled these episodes. As a fiction writer, this makes me very nervous. Now, who will believe the carefully invented traumas my characters recall? Will the characters even believe one another? One thing is clear. We've been doing a lot of revising.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL BLAINE  Jefferson, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
